# Advantages of MVC

### Separation of Concerns
Each layer has a specific responsibility, making the code easier to understand and maintain.

### Scalability
New features can be added by creating new models, controllers, and routes without affecting existing functionality.

### Maintainability
Changes in one layer have minimal impact on other layers, simplifying updates and debugging.

### Code Reusability
Business logic and database operations can be reused across multiple API endpoints.

### Easy Testing
Each layer can be tested independently, improving software quality and reducing bugs.

### Better Collaboration
Frontend and backend developers can work simultaneously on different components with minimal conflicts.

### Organized Project Structure
MVC keeps the project modular, making it easier for developers to navigate and contribute.

### Enhanced Security
Controllers handle validation and authentication before interacting with the database, ensuring secure data processing.

---

# Summary

The MVC architecture provides a structured and modular foundation for the SB Stocks application. By separating data management (Model), business logic (Controller), and request handling (View), the application becomes easier to maintain, extend, and scale. This architecture supports secure authentication, efficient portfolio management, real-time stock data processing, and reliable transaction handling while ensuring a clean and organized codebase.
